{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489470"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:17:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:17:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"667"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/667"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.16,0.06,0.07,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/667"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67703"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2149"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4838"},{"type":"tags","id":"5773"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9101"},{"type":"tags","id":"9108"},{"type":"tags","id":"9526"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22788"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39781"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThree days after a total knee replacement a 67-year-old man becomes confused, voluble and difficult to control. He had been making a good post-operative recovery until this episode started several hours earlier. His case notes record a known alcohol consumption of four glasses of wine a day, a 30 pack-year smoking history. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes for which he takes atenolol and metformin. On examination he is sitting on the edge of the bed, remonstrating with the nurses. A blood pressure recording taken two hours earlier was 100/70 mmHg, pulse rate 100/min and temperature 38.2C. Attempts at further examination at this stage proves fruitless because of his aggressiveness. He is persuaded to take an olanzapine wafer and once a little calmer, a septic screen is performed whilst waiting for the doctor to return to make a further assessment. The septic screen includes a chest X-ray (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Broad spectrum antibiotics and chest physiotherapy","Chest tube and underwater seal drain","CT chest and abdomen","CT pulmonary angiogram","Laparotomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has a pneumoperitoneum, as shown by the large volume of free gas under the right hemidiaphragm (Image). The explanation for the patient\u0027s confusion and clinical picture is likely to be sepsis secondary to perforation of an intra-abdominal viscus. Whilst it is sound medical practice to consider diagnostic parsimony (Occam\u0027s razor), it is unlikely that this patient\u0027s current problem is related to his orthopaedic procedure. Whilst a pulmonary embolus or pneumonia might lead to hypoxia and confusion, that would not explain the free gas - which is under the diaphragm and not in the pleural space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe obverse to Occam\u0027s razor is Hickam\u0027s dictum (\u0027A man can have as many diseases as he damn well pleases.\u0027). In this instance, once possible related causes have been considered and excluded, the clinician must broaden their mind and think of other, unrelated, possible causes. This vignette was a real case. The problem had arisen secondary to perforated diverticular disease. Once the patient had been quietened, with the aid of the olanzapine wafer, it became readily evident that he had peritonitis and was promptly taken to the operating room for a \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E and the perforation dealt with.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn many circumstances an abdominal CT scan can help in the diagnosis and planning of management of patients with acute abdominal pain. However, in this case it is very clear that the patient has a perforated abdominal viscus and requires prompt surgical intervention. Even if a CT scan did clarify the cause of the perforation, it would not change the plan of management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erect chest X-ray is an integral part the septic screen. It may show lung conditions but also can be useful to detect free subdiaphragmatic gas","A perforated viscus in an unwell patient warrants prompt surgical management"],"references":["Wong RE, Pabla BS, Gamboa AM. When Occam\u2019s Razor Meets Hickam\u2019s Dictum. Gastroenterology 2019; 155:e1-e3. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31150610/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67703"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"667"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18205"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20370"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18205"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/22dd97a0-978e-4bd9-a14c-472474cd246a.jpg